<TITLE> Egyptian Islamists say three members disappeared </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CAIRO, Aug 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Three young members of the Muslim Brotherhood have disappeared, three weeks after police detained them in the Egyptian city of Alexandria, their fathers told a news conference organised by the Brotherhood on Monday. Egyptian police regularly hold members of the Islamist movement without charge for months at a time but families can usually find out where they are and even visit them. But in the case of the three Alexandria men their families have not been able to obtain any information about who is holding them where, the fathers said. An Interior Ministry spokesman said he had no information about the three, named as Mohamed Ali Farid and two brothers, Mustafa and Mohamed Ahmed Mohamed Imam. The father of the two brothers said police took one of them from the family home on July 18 and the other was part of a group of Muslim Brotherhood members detained while at summer camp. The father of the third man said his son was picked up from the street while on the way home from a computer class. The Egyptian authorities are holding several hundred members of the Brotherhood, mostly without charge, as part of a crackdown which started late last year. The government calls the Brotherhood an illegal organisation but its members hold 88 seats in parliament and the group, which seeks an Islamic state through democratic elections, can operate with some limited freed
